{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:20:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22653"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22653"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111432"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93535"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6098"},{"type":"tags","id":"7230"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111432"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing difficulty holding small objects with his right hand. He can no longer pinch them firmly. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks about one can of beer daily. He works as a carpenter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On examination, some obvious changes can be seen in his right hand (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hAxL545PkFBSJeQvXsqDXLXpPG82IQ.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radial nerve entrapment","Ulnar nerve compression","Carpal tunnel syndrome","Atrophy of the abductor pollicis longus muscle","Atrophy of the flexor pollicis longus muscle"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ulnar nerve supplies most of the intrinsic muscles of the hand, including the interossei, lumbricals (third and fourth), adductor pollicis, and the hypothenar muscles. This patient presents with classic features of ulnar nerve compression, including wasting of the first dorsal interosseous muscle (visible as hollowing in the first web space) and weakness of pinch grip. Sensory changes may also be observed in the corresponding areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve compression\u003C/strong\u003E at the elbow (cubital tunnel syndrome) is common in manual workers who perform repetitive elbow flexion. The patient\u0027s occupation as a carpenter likely involves frequent elbow bending, which can compress the ulnar nerve as it passes through the cubital tunnel. The loss of pinch strength results from weakness of the adductor pollicis and first dorsal interosseous muscles, both supplied by the ulnar nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve entrapment\u003C/strong\u003E would cause wrist drop and weakness of finger extension, not the pattern of intrinsic muscle wasting and pinch weakness seen here. The radial nerve does not supply the intrinsic muscles of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves compression of the median nerve and would cause thenar muscle wasting (not first web space wasting), along with sensory symptoms in the median nerve distribution (thumb, index, middle, and radial half of ring finger). The patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are not consistent with median nerve pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrophy of the abductor pollicis longus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E would affect thumb abduction and extension, not the pinch grip weakness and first web space wasting seen here. This muscle is supplied by the posterior interosseous branch of the radial nerve and its isolated atrophy would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrophy of the flexor pollicis longus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E would cause weakness of thumb interphalangeal joint flexion, not the pattern of intrinsic muscle wasting and pinch weakness observed. This muscle is supplied by the anterior interosseous branch of the median nerve and lies in the forearm, not the hand.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ulnar nerve compression causes wasting of the first dorsal interosseous muscle, visible as hollowing in the first web space.","Cubital tunnel syndrome from repetitive elbow flexion is a common cause of ulnar nerve compression in manual workers.","Loss of pinch strength results from weakness of the adductor pollicis and first dorsal interosseous muscles supplied by the ulnar nerve."],"references":["Boone S, Gelberman RH, Calfee RP. The Management of Cubital Tunnel Syndrome. J Hand Surg Am. 2015; 40:1897-904. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26243318/","Silver S, Ledford CC, Vogel KJ, Arnold JJ. Peripheral Nerve Entrapment and Injury in the Upper Extremity. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Mar 1;103(5):275-285. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2021/0301/p275.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93535"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22021"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22021"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hAxL545PkFBSJeQvXsqDXLXpPG82IQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hAxL545PkFBSJeQvXsqDXLXpPG82IQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":399}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93535"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-13T22:19:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T22:20:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15600"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111432"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"ite